        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>Requested configurations: 
In order to obtain most accurate isotopic values, we need to separate equatorial and polar region where the temperature is significantly different.  Therefore, a  low resolution map (~3x3) will be needed as well as signal-to-noise ratio (SNR) better than 20 on C18O line. For mapping Titan’s disk  (~0.8”) we ask configuration C34-3, which provides a synthesized beam of 0.4” in band 7. Our simulations indicates that we do not expect any flux losses due to short spacing, since at our highest 354 GHz frequency,  the C34-3 configuration has a maximum angular scale (MAS) 6  times larger than the planet’s apparent diameter.

Frequency and Correlator setups: 
Band 7 provides the best SNR for a given integration time. Two frequency setups are needed to cover all the targeted lines (see the frequency sketch in Fig. 2). Setup-1 allows to observe the relatively narrow (~5-10 MHz) emission lines of C18O(3-2) at 329.330 GHz, 13CO(3-2) at 330.587 GHz and HC15N(4-3)  at 344.200 GHz.  Setup-2 covers HC15N(4-3) line at 344.200 GHz, H13CN(4-3)  at 345.339 GHz,  CO(3-2)  at 345.795 GHz and HCN(4-3) at 354.505 GHz.  Note that HC15N is present in both setups. As a by-product of the Setup-2, we target also several CH3CCH lines centered at 341.7 GHz. We have chosen the largest possible bandwidth in order to measure also the broad component of the CO isotopes, as well as the CO itself which influences the local continuum of the isotopes. Being constrained by the bit rate, we have performed a spectral average=2. It results in a spectral resolution of 1.13 MHz. 

Requested sensitivity: 
The narrow emission (FWHM ~5-10 MHz) lines probes mainly the stratosphere. A spectral resolution of 1.13 MHz is hereafter considered for the time estimates. Figs. 2 and 3 present our simulations of the line intensities assuming terrestrial isotopic ratios except for the 14N/15N ratio taken equal to 70 . A Gaussian beam convolution of 0.4” is also taken into account. The expected line intensities are of 700  mJy/Beam for the HC15N line,  88 mJy/beam for the C18O line, 600 mJy/beam for the H13CN line, and 333 mJy/beam for the 13CO line.  For the CO and HCN main species, strong fluxes, larger than 1 Jy/beam are predicted.

In order to have a robust SNR of ~20 on the weakest C18O  lines, the ALMA time estimator indicates 1.13 hour of total  time (i.e. a sensitivity 4.4 mJy/Beam) for setup 1.  We also ask for the same sensitivity for setup 2. The corresponding SNR for all lines will be ~20 for C18O, ~75 for 13CO , ~136 for H13CN and ~ 159 for the HC15N. Finally the SNR for CO and HCN will be &gt; 300.

Calibration: 
We will adopt the “system defined calibration”. Note that Titan itself will serve as our primary flux calibrator.  Self-calibration of the known continuum will allow us to obtain the best data quality.

Scheduling: 
We ask for a period close to the next Saturn opposition (27 May 2015) so that we can benefit from the
maximum apparent size of Titan (solid body angular diameter of 0.8”). The observing period must be centered near
Titan’s maximum elongation from Saturn not to suffer from Saturn contamination.  About 20 day per month are adequate for observing Titan, a list of all possible date will be furnished in due time. 

In summary, we ask for 2 spectral setups with a total observing time of 2.1 hour, using configuration C34-3.
</prj:justificationText>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
